		<item>
		<title>Help for freelancers non-payment going to court pt2</title>
		<link>http://louiscox.com/wordpress/?p=693</link>
		<comments>http://louiscox.com/wordpress/?p=693#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 31 Dec 2010 14:41:33 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Freelance]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[court case]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[freelance]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[non payment]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[prosecution]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[small claims]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://louiscox.com/wordpress/?p=693</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://louiscox.com/wordpress/?p=693"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="100" height="100" src="http://louiscox.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/jollyRoger-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" style="float:left; vertical-align: top; margin-right: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;" alt="Jolly roger" title="Jolly roger" /></a>Its my express wish to cover these articles to help out freelancers in similar circumstance and not to attack the reputation of any companies I may have worked with. It has to be said that in my experience as a freelancer all my clients are very good at paying and these cases are very much [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-303" style="vertical-align: top; float: left; margin-right: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;" title="Jolly roger" src="http://louiscox.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/jollyRoger.jpg" alt="Jolly roger" title="jollyRoger" width="300" height="211" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-303" />
Its my express wish to cover these articles to help out freelancers in similar circumstance and not to attack the reputation of any companies I may have worked with. It has to be said that in my experience as a freelancer all my clients are very good at paying and these cases are very much the exception to the rule. Its not that surprising that these cases have occurred during the height of a financial downturn. This case was a small claims case as opposed to a proper full court claim. Again Im interested in arming the fellow freelancer with the tools and a bit of inspiration to prosecute for non payment. Its not something I want to do as obviously it makes me look like I have been prosecuting lots of cases &#8211; which I haven&#8217;t &#8211; so far only two touch wood &#8211; both agencies. All the information is factually correct as happened to obviously cover myself from any prosecution. There is a lot of information regarding small claims. Its very easy these day and I did mine online, read below for full links.<br/>
<a href="http://www.thewalkeragency.co.uk/">The Walker agency</a>  headed by <a href=http://uk.linkedin.com/pub/martin-walker/15/9a6/537">Martin Walker</a> came to me across Twitter via another employee and asked for a Flash piece based on video. Its all seemed very fair, so I asked for a formal brief. It was critical I did this as later this was brought into question. Always ask for a formal brief. It is the yardstick for what you have produced. The tale of this client non payment is about them asking for alterations and refusing to pay for them. In a way this was a great shame as I quite enjoyed doing the job initially. It was a technical challenge. Essentially they wanted a portfolio that auto loaded separate flash movies and jpegs with various bits of animation and an interactive interface. Fair do&#8217;s. Unfortunately I personally made a mistake when I totally underestimated how much time would be required to technically resolve the problem. That basic problem was the video &#8211; which needed some fairly complex code to enable priority loading which the client had asked for. Ok &#8211; so once I found this out &#8211; immediately I told the client and said to him &#8211; <em>&#8220;Look, this is going to take a few weeks ( I had quoted one weeks costs at this point ) &#8211; and this is extra time that I am willing to pay for myself to enable the job.&#8221;</em> I am very clear to the client that the additional time I have spent will mean that there is very little room for manoeuvre when it comes to fishing at the end as I&#8217;ll have had to spend so much time off my own back. I will need paying for any alterations. I put this as politely as I can.<br/>
So, the client says &#8211; <em>&#8220;Ok thats fair enough. We want the solution and we don&#8217;t have to pay extra which your not asking for &#8211; great&#8221;</em>. There is no real deadline as its for us, not another client. All well and good. I build the code structure and realise that it requires some pretty carefully thought out sequence for the video and content &#8211; without going to the expense of using an abstract system that would use something like XML that could easily be edited &#8211; and using a class in AS3 etc. So I say to the client &#8211; <em>&#8220;Here are the choices &#8211; go for an abstract class and we can pretty much build anything and in fact you can change the sequence yourself. Anything you like. OR you can have a fixed sequence which will be much quicker and cheaper&#8221;</em>. So naturally &#8211; the client comes back right away and says &#8211; <em>&#8220;No can do on the XML ( in an Email mind you ) we need to keep the costs to a budget&#8221;</em>. So &#8211; Im on the case and start building the sequence. I send them a blow for blow example explaining how the sequence must be strict and alterations will require me re-making the item. So the client says &#8216;yes fine&#8217; without reading anything I have written. Come finishing the job some three weeks late which I had paid for and they were still asking for further alterations. <br/><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-303" style="vertical-align: top; float: left; margin-right: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; margin-top: 20px;" title="The Walker Agency" src="http://louiscox.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/walker_agency-300x204.jpg" alt="The Walker agency" title="The Walker Agency" width="300" height="204" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-699" / > 
Here ( graphic left ) is the basic layout as an example. Ok says the client &#8211; <em>&#8220;We need this video here and this video here and so on…&#8221;</em>. In reply I say <em>&#8220;Well I sent you this email that clearly says I will need to stick to a specific sequence for cost and speed&#8221;</em>. I outline the email by copy some of its content to the client. Then an argument ensues &#8211; in which I refuse to do the work for free having already done much gratis. The client eventually capitulates &#8211; with a very lengthy and drawn out argument. But everyone is happy and I continue. Three days extra are added to the production. Come the end of the three days &#8211; naturally additional requirements have delayed the finish. The client finally asks for a complete change to the video player and I decide enough is enough and ask for some additional time and cost. Again to cut a long story short the client refuses sign off and after nearly a months worth of unpaid work &#8211; for which I will be getting only just over a weeks pay I decide I have had enough. The client flatly refuses to believe that the changes he has requested are not in the brief. We go back to the brief. He still refuses to accept that its not a change he is asking for saying that the extra three days cover everything.<br/>
Now don&#8217;t get me wrong &#8211; ordinarily I will spend a bit of extra time covering a job. I don&#8217;t mind a couple of days if it happens and the client is a good one &#8211; pays on time and keeps coming back etc. But here we have such an extreme case that I can spend a few weeks extra getting something right &#8211; and the client totally ignores the good will I have put in to try and lever the exact item they want under the cloak of an estimate. An estimate is exactly that &#8211; just an estimate. It is not a cast iron jacket for cost so that you can be bent over by a client. I try and reason with the client &#8211; they are having none of it and insist that I produce what they want. I try repeatedly to sort it out of court. The client tries the classic tactic of implying I&#8217;m in some way unprofessional because I want to do this and that my work is substandard. We end up in court.<br/>
So, this is small claims &#8211; one court case up I know Im on easier territory. And it proves to be just that. Here are my important points as a freelancer to note. <br/><br/>
1. Get a formal brief by mail or if in person at a studio take copious notes even if that gets difficult. As for a summary of main points by email if they can &#8211; or send yours to them.<br/>
2. Be sure to provide an estimate, and mark it as an estimate or quote.<br/>
3. If the client is insistent on a fixed job cost &#8211; make sure you are totally happy with your time estimate, add some contingency and go back with the cost. If they don&#8217;t like it offer an estimate and cost extra work. Quoting for a job cost is a very risky business because you will have to be very strict with the client about not making changes. Under no circumstances should you end up working for free.<br/>
4. Bill weekly if possible. If its not &#8211; you must be sure to get all the details about payment / the payroll dept &#8211; if possible go and see them with your details and get them to send an email saying they have got them.<br/><br/>
So basically everything you need is at <a href="http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/">Government online court service</a>.
<br/><br/>Essentially there is no messing around here. You fill in the form with a precise description of what you have done and what is outstanding. The defendant then gets all the official paperwork. The cost is about £70 which gets added to the outstanding amount. The way it happened for me was the client finally agreed to pay some of the money in a rather rude letter &#8211; saying that I was still wrong. Ok &#8211; I said then lets continue and meet in court. Once you are on track for going to court its not really  worth folding for a few bob off &#8211; its all or nothing with small claims really. Eventually they paid without having to go to court &#8211; without any thanks and that may sound a bit harsh but then I didnt do anything wrong and created exactly what I was asked for so in reality I feel they are lucky I settled when I did. They said my work was substandard and not fit for requirement because they wanted me to work for free which is totally unacceptable from an agency. As I say I hope this helps any freelancers that unfortunately find themselves in the same position. Feel free to contact me regarding the case using the site email.<br/><br/>
]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://louiscox.com/wordpress/?feed=rss2&#038;p=693</wfw:commentRss>
