		<item>
		<title>Help for freelancers non-payment going to court pt1</title>
		<link>http://louiscox.com/wordpress/?p=679</link>
		<comments>http://louiscox.com/wordpress/?p=679#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 31 Dec 2010 11:39:52 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Freelance]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[bad client]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[court]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[freelance]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[non-payemnt]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[prosecution]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[small claims]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://louiscox.com/wordpress/?p=679</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://louiscox.com/wordpress/?p=679"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="100" height="100" src="http://louiscox.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/jollyRoger-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" style="float:left; vertical-align: top; margin-right: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;" alt="Jolly roger" title="Jolly roger" /></a>Its my express wish to cover these articles to help out freelancers in similar circumstance and not to attack the reputation of any companies I may have worked with. It has to be said that in my experience as a freelancer all my clients are very good at paying and these cases are very much [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-303" style="vertical-align: top; float: left; margin-right: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;" title="Jolly roger" src="http://louiscox.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/jollyRoger.jpg" alt="Jolly roger" title="jollyRoger" width="300" height="211" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-303" />
Its my express wish to cover these articles to help out freelancers in similar circumstance and not to attack the reputation of any companies I may have worked with. It has to be said that in my experience as a freelancer all my clients are very good at paying and these cases are very much the exception to the rule. Its not that surprising that these cases have occurred during the height of a financial downturn. The problem was I found very little info regarding particularly this &#8211; a major court case &#8211; not small claims. All the information is factually correct as happened to obviously cover myself from any prosecution. This case is regarding a situation where I was owed in excess of £5k by the client, and required the use of a lawyer to negotiate the case, and not a small claims case &#8211; which I have covered in part II.<br/>Ok, so Ive been waiting for a while to write this &#8211; namely until I had taken the case to court and received the payment. Essentially back in April 2009 I was asked by <a href="http://www.montash.com/">Montash Associates</a> via <a href="http://uk.linkedin.com/pub/dir/+/Larholt/gb-4573-London,-United-Kingdom">Andy Larholt</a> to create a website for them. I was working with a friend that was doing Copywrite to create the content for the site. We agreed that I would bill my friend and he would in turn bill the entire amount to the client. Ok, great we proceeded with the job. The client had already been to a company based in Brighton who he had thrown off the job because they had asked him to sign an agreement for payment which he refused to. This probably should have set off alarm bells really. So I proceed down the usual lines, produce a design document outlining everything to be created, time scales and a description of functionality. Next the graphic design was outlined. Here&#8217;s is a sample &#8211; if you compare it to the site you can see that even though the client tried to not pay the bill &#8211; effectively saying he was not happy with the site &#8211; he still used the design. <img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-303" style="vertical-align: top; float: left; margin-right: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; margin-top: 20px;" title="Montash Associates" src="http://louiscox.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/montash_1-300x214.gif" alt="Montash Asscoiates" title="montash_1" width="300" height="214" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-690" / > The graphic design was sent to the client &#8211; he agreed the design, asked for some Flash header work as seen in the existing site now ( a set of world clocks ) and he liked all of it. That section was paid of at 30% and we all got paid on time. So then no reason to suspect the client would in any way suddenly decide to not pay. <br/>The next phase was started. The company had an I.T. guy that had previously been doing the site. This should have been alarm bell number two, disgruntled ex site builder not happy about new guys coming in. So right from the beginning I ask to the main database that was being used via MySql. Needless to say, despite me chasing and phoning and repeatedly asking the client for the access it was not forth coming. The functionality of the site is all signed off and described in the design document &#8211; we already have the designs so it should really be a matter of just building it. <br/>After nearly a months delay &#8211; I eventually got the client to get all his ducks in a row and get the appropriate information from the right people. Great &#8211; the site is built and everything goes up. Fantastic. We tweak and tweak until it is exactly right. The client sees the first draft of the site as a functional click through and then we apply all the design and add the content. Of course its late due to the technical requirement for the back end. The client is happy with the click-through. The client is happy with the first draft but wants some final alterations. Nothing unusual. Second draft and suddenly there is a mysteriously aloof mail from the client outlining that he is not happy with the site because he has consulted &#8216;an independent&#8217; assessor. Hes not happy with the design ( the one he is still using ) or the functionality ( the one he has agreed to ). Despite a very strong letter of complaint I finally agree to make some of the changes in return for his agreement that he will sign off if I make them and pay. I refuse to do further work unless its paid for and the bill is settled up to date. I really did try and bend over backwards for the client but the basic problem was he did not want to pay for the site as I speculate that his former I.T. guy had offered a site build at a substantially reduced rate. So cut a long story shot &#8211; the client refuses to pay saying the site is late, not fit for purpose and generally poor quality.<br/>Its at this point that most people will just roll over and say &#8211; well its not worth the hassle. This is a tactic employed by many unscrupulous people in business, knowing full well that a prosecution will take much too long and cost way too much. I am here to tell you that if you are a freelancer and you have produced the work as required and the client is just trying it on &#8211; TAKE IT TO COURT. Get a good lawyer and go for it. You did the work &#8211; and nobody has the right to call you work defective when its not. This is another trick employed by unscrupulous business people &#8211; trying to make you feel guilty by saying your work is in some way not good enough. Ok, so assuming your still reading what do you do? I was lucky in the fact that I knew a good lawyer &#8211; and this lawyer was not an expensive, glossy office with potted plants type of place, rather a bread an butter lawyers in my local town who had happened to help me with some property legal matters. This in my opinion is often the way that it goes &#8211; look for a lawyers track record and not how imposing their office is. They might be good at prosecuting major court cases for wealthy clients but when they give a minor case to a junior &#8211; will they be able to cut the mustard? Anyway &#8211; so the buts and bolts of the matter are that a case worth more than £5k has to go to full court &#8211; otherwise it is allocated to small claims, but your lawyer should help you with all this &#8211; as that&#8217;s what they are paid for.<br/> Its worth noting here that it took me a whole year to get to court. Do not expect immediate payment. Going to court is not a quick solution. Small claims is slightly faster so my advice to to just keep billing down to weeks rather than months. We had to pay an initial fee of £500 in paperwork costs to get the ball rolling. Generally both parties will present their case &#8211; an opening gambit. Obviously expect your client to lie if they have tried not to pay &#8211; they will obviously try and get away with it even now. Duly my client tried to explain himself on the matter of subjective matters like design and functionality that was signed off. Even copy that was signed off was brought into question &#8211; all of which was of course ridiculous and I instructed my layer to press ahead. It was at this point that the client tried a dirty trick &#8211; the opposing layers sent word that they would use a clause that they believed we would not have the money to pay the costs should we loose the case. In many peoples mind this would have been a credible threat. To me &#8211; I just saw desperation and pressed the case on. Gradually the client began to realise we were committed to getting a result. Of a total outstanding approx £12k they came back with £2k, followed by £5k and eventually about 3/4 of the outstanding plus lawyers fees. Don&#8217;t forget to include lawyers fees as obviously its s significant amount &#8211; we paid around £3k. A small price given that we might have got nothing from billing of £12k, so well worth doing. Please feel free to write to me about any aspect of the case if I can help more than happy to do so&#8230;<br/><br/>]]></content:encoded>
