		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://louiscox.com/wordpress/?p=650"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="100" src="http://www.louiscox.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/PS31.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" style="float:left;  vertical-align: top; margin-right: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;" alt="PS3" title="PS3" /></a>DO NOT UPDATE YOUR PLAYSTATION. YOU ARE ARE SIGNING AWAY YOUR DIGITAL RIGHTS. What to do about charging? thats the question &#8211; whats the profit model? whats the revenue stream? The whole of the gigantic profit making machine that fuelled the post war generations media consumption, stood motionless like a rabbit in the headlights for [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-189" title="PS3" src="http://www.louiscox.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/PS31.jpg" alt="PS3" width="116" height="75" /><br/><br/><br/>
DO NOT UPDATE YOUR PLAYSTATION. YOU ARE ARE SIGNING AWAY YOUR DIGITAL RIGHTS.<br/><br/>
What to do about charging? thats the question &#8211; whats the profit model? whats the revenue stream? The whole of the gigantic profit making machine that fuelled the post war generations media consumption, stood motionless like a rabbit in the headlights for years as the internet grew from a back-room curio into a fully fledged media monster. Where would these profits come from, who would police the internet?. Open access has become the evil byword to new media profiteers. Now the spell is lifted and they are darting in any direction, desperate to avoid the wheels of progress. Knee jerk solutions are of course rife. Enter DRM, enter Cinavia. Of course conveniently ignoring consumer rights and creating a faster turnover of general consumption is par for the course.<br/>
When I bought my PS3 back in 2009 I naturally assumed that I would be buying exactly what was described to me in all the adds. It was a very open platform with all the bells and whistles. Gradually during the course of the year, its changed from a really neat all in one media player games platform to a Sony Box into which you shove money and things you don&#8217;t want come out. Originally you could install Linux or Gnome. Originally there was no simultaneous sampling of media being played causing problems. Originally you could uninstall software and downgrade if you wanted. Now its all locked down. You can only plug it into the phone line and everything is controlled for you by Sony. Did I buy that? No I did not &#8211; so heed my warning &#8211; DO NOT UPDATE YOUR PLAYSTATION.<br/>
Sony&#8217;s official line was feel free not to upgrade &#8211; but if you don&#8217;t nothings going to work. Ok &#8211; seems fair. The thing that gets stuck in my craw is that there is a &#8216;if you don&#8217;t read the small print&#8217; tough titty policy. The worst culprit for this is the removal of the ability to install a secondary OS. This was removed without any type of real indication to the users because Sony knew full well that it would upset a certain group of consumers. In reality its totally negation of consumer rights. In reality I should be able to send my playstation back to Sony and they should be forced to install the original OS. Because you have the install you have automatically agreed to the way Sony have done things. Hence &#8211; you are signing away your digital rights.<br/>
Then there is the issue of the Cinavia. Sony probably have more of a case for anti piracy here, but even so they should as a courtesy alert the user to the fact that the download alters the OS in very fundamental ways. Since OS version 3.1, the SP3 has had this bit of software that basically has an ear listening to audio played via Disc/mp4 or whatever and if it hears the embedded audio noise it shuts the play down. Its basically to stop the cinema recordings that go on. However of course it will be convenient to also stop the copying of films turned into Blu-ray. Apparently Sony have already run into problems with the network version of films with this encoding type. Im basically of the mind that no matter how much large business tries to justify the use of this type of encryption &#8211; its the artists, its the people working on backroom jobs etc &#8211; its simply the accounts department coming up with increasingly clever ways to plug the revenue holes. The more they do it, the more lone programmers find ways of drilling new ones. Just recently the coding for HDMI has been cracked as well, which will mean further problems for the studios. <br/>
I wish they would just accept that there will be a certain amount of piracy and not try and bugger up everyone&#8217;s equipment by trying to place anti piracy at the top of the list and not delivering what the consumer wants, and we as the consumers are the idiots that keep buying it and not complaining to the manufacturers.<br/>
That said &#8211; is anyone doing anything about it? Yes fortunately for us. The brilliant <a href="http://www.ps3-hacks.com">ps3 hacks</a> where there is a whole collection of software and information. Also <a href="http://christechtv.com/ ">Chris Tech T.V.</a>- a great collection of tips on how to jailbreak the PS3.<br/><br/>]]></content:encoded>
